Photo: Steve Gonzalez/Houston Chronicle Image 45 of 45 Flash flood watch cancelled 1 / 45 Back to Gallery Forecasters said to expect rainfall through the afternoon, but the National Weather Service called off the city's flash flood watch just before 8 a.m.
The city of Houston and Harris County had prepared for water rescues and flooding Monday morning, but by 7 a.m., the weather system moderated locally. Harris County's emergency management office said it would return to normal operations by 10 a.m.
Still, local airports delayed flights and some homes are without power.
Both Bush Intercontinental Airport and Hobby Airport lifted ground stops by 8:45 a.m., but many departures and arrivals out of each hub were delayed.
WEATHER ALERT: Big storm system to invade Houston area
CenterPoint Energy reported 3,527 power outages, clustered in the Energy Corridor and in Spring Shadows, as of 7:40 a.m. But nearly 2,000 households saw power return by 9:40 a.m.
The Harris County Flood Warning System reported after 9 a.m. that water is near the top of the banks of two small creeks northwest of Cypress. Other waterways fell below warning levels.
SEE THE DAMAGE: Incoming Houston storms also impacted San Antonio
Houston ISD officials said the district would operate on schedule. Some other districts were off Monday, or were teach in-service days only, due to the President's Day holiday.
The University of Houston said at 6:20 a.m. that it would operate on a normal schedule.
Check the latest forecast at weather.chron.com .
